{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13816"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13816"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.13,0.3,0.18,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113184"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95211"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46739"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113184"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a 24-hour history of severe pain in his right great toe. He states it has kept him awake all night and has been progressively worsening. He remembers having a similar episode about three years ago that self-resolved after two days. He reports that he stubbed his toe the day prior, sustaining a small wound that he dressed, but there was no immediate pain afterwards until today. He has a medical history of hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, and well controlled type 2 diabetes for which he takes perindopril, hydrochlorothiazide, rosuvastatin, and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has obvious swelling and erythema of his right great toe (Image) with severe pain elicited with even light touch over his metatarsophalangeal joint. His vital signs are within normal limits and the wound appears as a small superficial graze on the end of the toe.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment to initiate for this acute episode?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Naproxen","Flucloxacillin","Colchicine","Intra-articular corticosteroid injection","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a classic acute gout attack, with severe pain, erythema, and swelling of the first metatarsophalangeal joint, also known as \u0027podagra\u0027 when involving this joint. The patient\u0027s comorbidities and medication history are highly relevant to management choices. Review of the patient\u0027s medications is also warranted, as thiazide diuretics can exacerbate gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGuidelines now suggest initiating urate-lowering therapy (ULT) like allopurinol during an acute attack, provided that flare prophylaxis (colchicine or prednisolone) is prescribed. However, the immediate priority is to treat the acute episode: first-line options including NSAIDs and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorticosteroids (prednisolone)\u003C/strong\u003E, with colchicine being considered second-line for acute treatment. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment to initiate for this acute episode. Oral corticosteroids are considered first-line therapy for acute gout, especially in patients at increased risk of acute kidney injury from non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs. Short-term use for approximately 3-5 days or until the symptoms subside is an effective and well-tolerated treatment option for gout. Short courses of steroids will have little impact on a patients glycaemic control, especially when only requiring oral hypoglycaemic agents. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is due to the risk of gastrointestinal side effects and drug interactions with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolchicine\u003C/strong\u003E, especially in people with comorbidities or polypharmacy. The concept of \u0027treat to target\u0027 should be followed; that is, aiming serum urate target \u0026lt;0.36 mmol/L after complete crystal dissolution and resolution of gout (lower targets may be required in chronic tophaceous gout \u0026lt;0.30 mmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaproxen\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug and is generally first-line for acute gout in otherwise healthy individuals. However, in this patient, the addition of an NSAID to his regular medications would be unsafe due to the \u0022triple whammy\u0022 of an NSAID (naproxen), ACE inhibitor (perindopril), and diuretic (hydrochlorothiazide) placing the patient at risk of acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there was evidence of bacterial infection such as cellulitis, but the clinical features and history are more consistent with acute gout than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntra-articular corticosteroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable option for acute monoarticular gout, particularly if oral therapy is contraindicated or not tolerated. However, in primary care, oral prednisolone is more practical and less invasive, and there is no mention of contraindications to oral therapy in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prednisolone is an appropriate first-line treatment for acute gout in patients at risk of acute kidney injury from non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs.","Allopurinol can be safely initiated during an acute gout attack, but should be co-prescribed with colchicine to reduce the risk of flare.","The combination of a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor, and a diuretic increases the risk of acute kidney injury."],"references":["Graf SW, Whittle SL, Wechalekar MD, et al. Australian and New Zealand recommendations for the diagnosis and management of gout: integrating systematic literature review and expert opinion in the 3e Initiative. Int J Rheum Dis. 2015;18(3):341-351. doi:10.1111/1756-185X.12557","Quality Use of Medicines Alliance. Gout Treatment Algorithm [Internet]. Medcast. 2025 [cited 2025 May 4]. Available from: https://go.medcast.com.au/gout-treatment-algorithm","Gout [published 2024 December]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; . accessed 21 January 2025.https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95211"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13816"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20763"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20763"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9szH8EM6V0Zfb4V9Fh9QJkNQJmhTpg.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9szH8EM6V0Zfb4V9Fh9QJkNQJmhTpg.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95211"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T11:25:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T11:25:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","i